! instantiated-by: Timebox the Core (Agent-Facing)
  + context: An agent operates within fixed-duration interactive sessions (e.g. a 90-minute MAS workshop).
  + if: It aims to support the full cycle of inquiry (Situation → Scenario → Reflection).
  + however: Signals of saturation appear in attention, compute, or feedback channels.
  + then: Dynamically re-focus on the core loop, down-regulate peripheral prompts, and clearly signal completion of a concise iteration.
  + because: Respecting finite attention and resources preserves trust in the agent and the protocol.
  + next-steps:
    - Log one concrete instance of this pattern in the futon3 ledger.
  + evidence-base:
    - Timeboxing in agile practice shows that scoped iterations sustain engagement and reduce overload.
    - Interactive system design highlights the importance of adapting behaviour to real-time feedback on user capacity.


